node.text: Short film by @taylorglenn | We all know people whose dedication to a passion or purpose inspires us deeply. Gannett Horn's (@surfasaur) focus on his sport and love for its community embodies the best in each of us. This short film is a testament to Gannett and those who motivate us to work harder at the things we love. #riversurfing Production by @apresvisuals

node.text: Photos by @donaldmiralle / Day 11 was a wet and wild one at the track. A torrential downpour added to the atmosphere of the men’s steeplechase final, women’s 5,000m final, and semis of the women’s 400m hurdles and 200m. It’s been 90 degrees and 90% humidity all week, so the rain was welcomed to cool us off. Hope it rains all week! 🌧 (Athletes pictured @sydneymclaughlin16 @dalilahmuhammad_ @sifanhassan @soufianeelbakkaliofficiel)

node.text: Photo by @andy_best / It's bizarre how life on the road provides such a roller coaster of emotions. One day everything is broken, the kids are screaming, the weather is garbage, and the next day you are on cloud nine surrounded by beautiful humans in an unimaginable place. I always compare it to playing golf. If you play anything like me, it's terrible most of the way until that one glorious shot, or two! It'll keep you going back forever and pumped even longer.

node.text:
Photo by @donaldmiralle / On day nine of the Tokyo Olympics I made the long trip out to Enoshima Harbor for the Men’s and Women’s Windsurfer Gold Medal Final. In this photo, the men race in light afternoon winds while a coast guard boat sits off shore in the distance. 

Almost two hours away by car in traffic, it’s a totally different world from Tokyo. There are plenty of wide open beaches and harbors that are perfect for surfing and paddling that made me a little homesick for San Diego. Go to @natgeointhefield & @donaldmiralle to see more #behindthescenes and Olympic stories from the #TokyoOlympics

Self-portrait, Jasper National Park.

node.text: Photo by @ming.t.poon / @codytownsend skiing through the inversion layer near his home in Lake Tahoe. We had been shut down by an inversion; it seemed as if we were in a Ping-Pong ball. Right around sunset, the sun reflected off the clouds above and into this inversion layer, creating a pink hue. It was incredible, perfectly diffused light. We scrambled to get a few shots, including this one, then the light was gone within 5 minutes. Get it while you can!
